# Git: commit and push agreed changes

When you and the user agree on a batch of code or config changes in this repo:

1. Stage all relevant files (`git add` for the touched paths, or `git add -A` when the whole change set is intentional).
2. Write a clear commit message (what changed and why, in full sentences).
3. Run `git commit` and `git push` to `origin` on the current branch (usually `main`), unless the user explicitly asks to skip push or use a feature branch.

Do not leave agreed work only on disk without committing—deployed apps (e.g. Render) track the remote.

If push fails (auth, network), report the error and what remains to do; do not claim the push succeeded.
